2500|$|Although snow covers Crater Lake National Park {{for eight}} {{months of the year}} (average annual {{snowfall}} is [...] ), the lake rarely freezes over due in part to a relatively mild onshore flow from the Pacific Ocean. The last recorded year in which the lake froze over was in 1949, a very long, cold winter. A 95% surface freeze occurred in 1985. The immense depth of Crater Lake acts as a <b>heat</b> <b>reservoir</b> that absorbs and traps sunlight, maintaining the lake temperature at an average of [...] on the surface and [...] at the bottom throughout the year. The surface temperature fluctuates a bit, but the bottom temperature remains quite constant.|$|E
