50|$|Using the oil as a <b>heat</b> <b>reservoir,</b> {{the heating}} element heats the oil, which remains warm {{for a long}} period of time while the heat is {{transferred}} to the metal wall through convection, through the walls via conduction, then to the surroundings via convection and radiation. The columns of oil heaters are typically constructed as thin fins, such that the surface area of the metal columns is large relative to the volume of the oil <b>heat</b> <b>reservoir.</b> A large surface area allows more air to be in contact with the heater at any point in time, allowing for the heat to be transferred more rapidly from the heater into the room.|$|E
